## Summary of Findings

### CSS Analysis (From DevTools Console)
The hover CSS rule for Wave/Ripple buttons is:
```css
:is(.wave, .chip, .button, button, nav.tabbed > a, .tabs > a, nav.toolbar > a):not(.slow-ripple, .ripple, .fast-ripple):is(:focus-visible, :hover)::after { 
  /* hover visual feedback via ::after pseudo-element */
  background-size: ...; /* transition effect */
}
```

### Key Finding: **BUG CONFIRMED**
The CSS rule explicitly uses `:not(.slow-ripple, .ripple, .fast-ripple)` to **EXCLUDE** elements with the `.ripple` class from getting the hover `::after` visual feedback effect.

**Result**: The `.ripple` class does NOT have hover visual feedback (no background color change, no highlight on hover).

The `.wave` class DOES have hover visual feedback (the `::after` pseudo-element creates a subtle overlay/highlight on hover).

This appears to be an intentional design choice - `.ripple` is meant to only show animation on click (ripple effect), while `.wave` shows both hover effects AND wave animation. However, from a UX perspective, having NO hover feedback on an interactive button (`.ripple`) could be considered a bug or a confusing UX issue, as users expect some visual feedback when hovering over interactive elements.

